<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06156b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06156b">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06156b"> 156(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> coveters &mdash; idolaters</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">TENTH COMMANDMENT. &ldquo;THOU SHALT NOT COVET THY NEIGHBOUR&apos;S HOUSE, THOU SHALT NOT COVET THY NEIGHBOUR&apos;S WIFE, NOR HIS SERVANT, NOR HIS MAID, NOR HIS OX, NOR HIS ASS, NOR ANY THING THAT IS HIS.&rdquo;&mdash;This commandment teaches that the law is spiritual, that its commands extend to the desires of the soul and spirit, as well as to the actions of <font color="green">[38]</font> the body. To covet is to desire what is another&apos;s. <mark>The covetous man is called by St. Paul an idolater</mark>, because he trusts in uncertain riches, &ldquo;which some coveting after, they have erred from the faith and pierced themselves through with many sorrows.&rdquo; <small> Anonymous, <a name="ATCC" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ATCC"><cite title="source">Analysis of the Church Catechism</cite></a> (1879) 38-9</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
